    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Slaves and Soldiers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barbara J Fields letter replies to June 7 letter suggesting that if heirs of slaves are entitled to reparations, so are heirs of Union soldiers who died in Civil War</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 7 letter suggests that if heirs of slaves are entitled to reparations, so are the heirs of Union soldiers who died in the Civil War.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 7 letter suggests that if heirs of slaves are entitled to reparations, so are the heirs of Union soldiers who died in the Civil War.</p>
        <p>Leave aside the question of reparations for slavery. Leave aside the question of reparations for the heirs of other American soldiers, including those who died fighting Nazism, those who died fighting the British monarchy and those who died imposing colonial authority over the Philippines and Puerto Rico.</p>
        <p>The most interesting question is whether the letter writer proposes equal reparations to the heirs of white Union soldiers, who received $13 a month plus a $3 allowance for their uniforms, and the heirs of those black Union soldiers who had to accept $10 a month minus a $3 allowance for their uniforms.</p>
        <p>BARBARA J. FIELDS  New York, June 7, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of history at Columbia University.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
